<subSubSection id="2FB0C7008673E9A34BB0D66CF0F38C45" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="5E793CFF070EDC2DEE26CE07D1CDC30B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A7E9A0640C711BD00FB42A9EBCEFC91A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
While difficult to differentiate from a number of Palaearctic taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="40F82307171134EB26C5AA397BEA5BCE" authorityName="Strobl" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza apfelbecki" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apfelbecki">
<emphasis id="A09A7A1BBEB095292E7D4A4FEDB09955" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza apfelbecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite distinct from Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4DC506980AB010DE3DAD0C5FE99A0D6A" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D4D2391A4455F21EE4BC5933740EA173" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it is exceptionally large (wing length at least 4.0 mm), there are numerous dorsocentrals (at least six), the epistoma is large and pronounced, the head is predominantly pale (including the palpus and face) and the halter is sometimes maculated. 
<taxonomicName id="1ABF7C599C70D762620E2570A70DF029" authorityName="Strobl" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza apfelbecki" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apfelbecki">
<emphasis id="F9BA17D46AB62FA66336C5F17D5A2247" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza apfelbecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of only three 
<taxonomicName id="7C1CA0B344D5E058E46813BCBCF24373" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FAA5F223D60E5E6B0E8304A037C8D40B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to feed on 
<taxonomicName id="7801DC0361B17E910A55221F547B2727" class="Insecta" family="Asteraceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
, and is distributed primarily around the Mediterranean where it often occurs on globe artichoke (Spencer, 1990).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5559E86D21054E44A273BC5CA8C1AA97" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The above Virginia record is the first known occurrence of this species in the Nearctic, where it was likely introduced accidentally on its host plant. As discussed by 
<bibRefCitation id="324D08AAFB9BD0594A261543AE209B31" author="Dempewolf, M" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="https://nlbif.eti.uva.nl/bis/agromyzidae.php" refId="B42" refString="Dempewolf, M, 2004. Arthropods of Economic Importance - Agromyzidae of the World (CD-ROM). ETI. University of Amsterdam, Amsterdam. https://nlbif.eti.uva.nl/bis/agromyzidae.php" title="Arthropods of Economic Importance - Agromyzidae of the World (CD-ROM). ETI. University of Amsterdam, Amsterdam." url="https://nlbif.eti.uva.nl/bis/agromyzidae.php" year="2004">Dempewolf (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FB4159CF4351B86EBBCF3E1DD70A5021" authorityName="Strobl" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Agromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agromyza apfelbecki" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apfelbecki">
<emphasis id="05D68A8E178B2C89BD337B42FA305F9B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Agromyza apfelbecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be a 
<taxonomicName id="F901112B46BD7CDDD78634AB0CF5781C" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Plantago" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plantago major" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">Plantago major</taxonomicName>
pest on artichoke if populations become large enough, particularly to younger plants; the damage caused by larval feeding can vary significantly between years (Spencer 1973), possibly due to climatic conditions, as frost can severely increase mortality among larvae (
<bibRefCitation id="38A5FD73EAE9CF0D40A27649678C17A9" author="Ricchello, A" journalOrPublisher=") Opredelitel nasekomyh evropejskoj casti SSSR (Leningrad)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B198" refString="Ricchello, A, 1928. Contributo alla conoscenza della mosca del carciofo (Agromyza andalusiaca Strobl) e dei suoi parassiti. Bolletino del Laboratorio di Zoologia Generale e Agraria del R Istituto Superiore Agrario i Portici 22: 81-147." title="Contributo alla conoscenza della mosca del carciofo (Agromyza andalusiaca Strobl) e dei suoi parassiti. Bolletino del Laboratorio di Zoologia Generale e Agraria del R Istituto Superiore Agrario i Portici 22: 81 - 147." year="1928">Ricchello 1928</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
